properties.Summary:

properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system over New England will approach the Maritimes today and cross the region on Friday. A band of very strong southeasterly winds gusting to 90 km/h will spread across Nova Scotia today, starting in the southwest early this morning, and reaching the eastern Mainland and Cape Breton this afternoon. properties.Title: High Water Level Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels are expected or occurring. An intense low pressure system tracking toward the region will give severe easterly winds this afternoon and evening. These water levels will result in flooding along coastlines and potential erosion to beaches and damage to infrastructure. ### Coastal flooding is likely, especially during high tide. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. High water level warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. For more information monitor Canadian Coast Guard radio or Weatheradio stations.

properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. An area of high pressure situated over the Arctic Ocean and an intense low pressure system over the Gulf of Alaska will continue to produce conditions favourable for strong, gusty winds near the Richardson Mountains. The strong winds, falling snow and existing snow pack will combine to produce blizzard conditions through at least Friday. ### Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather in British Columbia or Yukon, send an email to BCstorm@canada.ca or YTstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #BCStorm or #YTStorm.

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 15 cm is expected. A disturbance tracking northeastward out of the Northwest Territories will bring snow to the Baker Lake area today and tonight. Snow, at times heavy, is expected to develop late this morning or early this afternoon and persist during the evening before tapering off to light snow overnight. In addition to the snow strong southeasterly winds gusting at times to 70 km/h are expected today resulting in some blowing snow. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. properties.Title: Storm Surge Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Higher than normal water levels and large waves are expected near the coast this afternoon. Warning of potential breaking sea conditions and overwash issued jointly by Fisheries and Oceans Canada (Science) and the Meteorological Service of Canada - Quebec area on 2019-10-17. An intense low pressure system moving up the Eastern Seaboard will give strong to high northeasterly winds over the areas listed below today. The combination of these winds and the fact that we are currently in a period of medium tidal range could produce minor breaking sea conditions along the coast near these localities, at the dates and times specified (Eastern Daylight Time). Rimouski - Mont-Joli: 2019-10-17, from 3 PM to 7 PM. Matane: 2019-10-17, from 3 PM to 7 PM. Forillon Park - Gaspé - Percé: 2019-10-17, from 2 PM to 8 PM. New-Carlisle - Chandler: 2017-10-17, from 3 PM to 7 PM. ### Coastal flooding is possible along the shoreline. Coastal erosion is possible in vulnerable areas. Storm surge warnings are issued when water levels pose a threat to coastal regions. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
